issue(id="0014" status="closed")
  title Formalize safe guest and base-image upgrade procedures
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer applying NixOS, kernel, or scrubs-module updates
    i-want one standard upgrade procedure for running guests and reusable base images
    so-that routine updates become consistent, documented, and low-risk instead of depending on memory or ad hoc judgment
  premise.
    Scrubs currently has the core mechanics needed to roll forward guest
    systems: the `vms` flake pins guest inputs, bootstrap can apply the current
    configuration inside an existing guest, and `just refresh-base-image` can
    rebuild the reusable qcow2 artifact from the latest scrubs state.

    What is still missing is a formal maintainer-facing pattern that explains
    when to use each path, how to verify success, and how to avoid surprises
    around staged-but-not-running kernels, stale base images, or long-lived
    guests drifting away from the current intended system shape.

    The goal of this task is not "make upgrades automatic at all costs." The
    goal is to define a standard, documented, conservative procedure for
    routine scrubs system updates that can be repeated safely. That procedure
    should cover both in-place guest updates and base-image refreshes, and it
    should include validation and recovery guidance strong enough that the
    default operator experience feels boring rather than risky.

    This is now effectively settled. The operative answer is to keep guest
    updates explicit and artifact-driven: use automated NixOS updates where
    they help maintain the intended base state, then re-bootstrap or recreate
    guests from the new flake when the refreshed image should become the new
    default.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented upgrade model that clearly distinguishes at least three cases: patching a long-lived guest in place, refreshing the reusable base image artifact, and recreating project guests from a refreshed base image.
    criterion The documented procedure explains how flake input bumps, scrubs module changes, `nixos-rebuild` inside guests, guest restarts, and `just refresh-base-image` relate to one another.
    criterion The standard upgrade path defines explicit validation steps for both configured state and running state, including checks for the active kernel or generation after any required reboot.
    criterion The standard upgrade path includes a conservative recovery story, such as when to keep the previous base image, when to stage changes into a disposable maintenance guest first, and how to avoid turning one failed update into fleet-wide guest breakage.
    criterion At least one maintainer-oriented command sequence or helper flow exists that encodes the recommended upgrade procedure rather than leaving it entirely as README prose.
    criterion The final guidance makes clear which update paths are intended to be routine and low-risk, and which still require exceptional care or manual judgment.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      The default upgrade model is now explicit in the operator docs. The
      current routine path is: refresh or rebuild the base image when the new
      flake should become the new default, validate it, and then recreate
      project guests from that image. In-place `nixos-rebuild` remains
      available for long-lived guests that intentionally need patching without
      replacement, but it is no longer treated as the main fleet-wide answer.
    item(status="covered").
      A heavyweight rollback or A/B image-promotion system is not currently
      justified. The documented retention model already keeps rollback boring:
      preserve prior qcow2 artifacts by name, validate before replacing the
      working image, and mirror important base images outside the repo. That
      gives maintainers a conservative recovery story without adding more
      machinery.
    item(status="covered").
      The task's validation concern is effectively satisfied by the README's
      existing regression baseline and patch model rather than a separate
      upgrade-specific framework.
